To set the text color to red in CSS, you use the `color` property. You can apply this in a few different ways depending on your needs:

### 1. Using a Class (Recommended)
This is the most common and reusable approach. Define a class in your CSS file and apply it to any HTML element.

**CSS:**
```css
.red-text {
  color: red;
}
```

**HTML:**
```html
<p class="red-text">This text is red.</p>
```

### 2. Using an Inline Style
Use this for quick tests or single-use cases, though it's generally less maintainable than using classes.

**HTML:**
```html
<p style="color: red;">This text is red.</p>
```

### 3. Using Specific Red Values
While `red` is a valid keyword, you might want a specific shade. You can use hex codes, RGB, or HSL values:

```css
/* Hex code */
color: #ff0000;

/* RGB */
color: rgb(255, 0, 0);

/* HSL */
color: hsl(0, 100%, 50%);
```

